1
00:00:05,932 --> 00:00:08,273
Without further ado, welcome to Beyond Game Design.

2
00:00:08,273 --> 00:00:09,534
So my name is Richard Carrillo,

3
00:00:09,534 --> 00:00:11,495
I'm a game director at Ubisoft Toronto,

4
00:00:11,495 --> 00:00:13,536
and today I'll be discussing what I consider

5
00:00:13,536 --> 00:00:16,698
to be one of the greatest challenges in this profession.

6
00:00:16,698 --> 00:00:18,179
And that challenge is working

7
00:00:18,179 --> 00:00:20,580
with the other developers around us,

8
00:00:20,580 --> 00:00:24,043
passionate developers who will analyze every design,

9
00:00:24,043 --> 00:00:25,643
they will pitch alternate solutions,

10
00:00:25,643 --> 00:00:27,545
they will question every direction.

11
00:00:27,545 --> 00:00:29,866
And for designers, this can lead to a lot of frustrations.

12
00:00:29,866 --> 00:00:31,547
And I want to do this talk

13
00:00:31,867 --> 00:00:37,092
Because a lot of times I've seen those frustrations become bigger conflicts on the team

14
00:00:37,092 --> 00:00:42,257
So how can we as designers embrace that passion that they have and channel it to make the best game possible?

15
00:00:42,257 --> 00:00:44,839
Instead of fighting against it and that's what I'll be talking about today

16
00:00:44,839 --> 00:00:51,606
This talk looks beyond the hard skills beyond game design to explore the soft skills that I believe every designer needs in order to build

17
00:00:51,606 --> 00:00:54,428
A positive design culture on the team

18
00:00:54,428 --> 00:00:55,710
so but first

19
00:00:57,258 --> 00:00:59,259
I've been in the industry for 14 years.

20
00:00:59,259 --> 00:01:00,819
In that time, I've been lucky to be a part

21
00:01:00,819 --> 00:01:02,680
of five major different studios.

22
00:01:02,680 --> 00:01:04,681
Each studio was filled with honestly amazing

23
00:01:04,681 --> 00:01:06,561
and talented people, and each had

24
00:01:06,561 --> 00:01:07,942
a completely different design culture.

25
00:01:07,942 --> 00:01:10,803
And what I mean by design culture is

26
00:01:10,803 --> 00:01:12,684
they all have different ideas on what designers should own,

27
00:01:12,684 --> 00:01:15,265
the design process to get approvals,

28
00:01:15,265 --> 00:01:17,146
and also who should be a part of that process.

29
00:01:17,146 --> 00:01:19,166
So all of these experiences have helped me

30
00:01:19,166 --> 00:01:22,128
to really solidify the design culture I promote on my teams,

31
00:01:22,128 --> 00:01:23,608
and that's what I wanna kinda show you today.

32
00:01:24,586 --> 00:01:27,930
Also, in these 14 years, I've been really lucky to be a part of some amazing projects.

33
00:01:27,930 --> 00:01:32,756
I've learned so much from these teams, and especially the latest we've shipped at Ubisoft

34
00:01:32,756 --> 00:01:34,298
Toronto, Starlink Battle for Atlas.

35
00:01:35,858 --> 00:01:38,120
And I want to talk a little bit about that game,

36
00:01:38,120 --> 00:01:39,560
just because I do take some examples

37
00:01:39,560 --> 00:01:42,622
from that development process and put in this presentation.

38
00:01:42,622 --> 00:01:44,543
So I want to make sure you guys have a good idea

39
00:01:44,543 --> 00:01:46,143
of what that game is.

40
00:01:46,143 --> 00:01:48,364
So Starlink is an open-world action-adventure game

41
00:01:48,364 --> 00:01:50,645
set in the massive star system called Atlas.

42
00:01:50,645 --> 00:01:52,386
In this game, you'll be battling against

43
00:01:52,386 --> 00:01:54,887
an ever-growing enemy threat called the Forgotten Legion,

44
00:01:54,887 --> 00:01:56,028
who are taking over each planet.

45
00:01:56,028 --> 00:01:58,489
So in short, it's a vehicular third-person shooter

46
00:01:58,489 --> 00:02:00,550
with a simulated enemy invasion

47
00:02:00,550 --> 00:02:03,211
that spreads across the star system in real time.

48
00:02:03,211 --> 00:02:04,452
And I'm not sure if that cleared things up,

49
00:02:04,452 --> 00:02:04,972
but I hope it did.

50
00:02:06,440 --> 00:02:08,362
So for now, back to the soft skills.

51
00:02:08,362 --> 00:02:08,902
Oh, went too far.

52
00:02:08,902 --> 00:02:12,066
So the main question for today is how do we build

53
00:02:12,066 --> 00:02:14,108
a positive design culture in our teams?

54
00:02:14,108 --> 00:02:15,689
And before we can really understand that,

55
00:02:15,689 --> 00:02:17,491
we need to understand all the day-to-day interactions

56
00:02:17,491 --> 00:02:19,233
that are maybe problematic that lead us

57
00:02:19,233 --> 00:02:20,394
to a negative design culture.

58
00:02:20,394 --> 00:02:21,796
And hopefully I can convince you

59
00:02:21,796 --> 00:02:22,877
that that's not what we want.

60
00:02:23,982 --> 00:02:26,202
I call these problems negative mindsets.

61
00:02:26,202 --> 00:02:28,563
So negative mindsets are the interactions we have

62
00:02:28,563 --> 00:02:31,544
with developers around us that sort of push them away.

63
00:02:31,544 --> 00:02:33,264
And I think it's safe to say that almost everyone

64
00:02:33,264 --> 00:02:34,424
in this room is guilty of these

65
00:02:34,424 --> 00:02:35,285
at some point in their career.

66
00:02:35,285 --> 00:02:38,265
And I'll go through some of the most common examples,

67
00:02:38,265 --> 00:02:40,046
and if you leave this talk with anything,

68
00:02:40,046 --> 00:02:41,266
I hope it's that you catch yourself

69
00:02:41,266 --> 00:02:43,547
whenever you say some of these or even think them.

70
00:02:43,547 --> 00:02:45,867
The first one.

71
00:02:45,867 --> 00:02:47,228
I'm the designer, let me do my job.

72
00:02:48,355 --> 00:02:50,417
So this is honestly one of the biggest examples

73
00:02:50,417 --> 00:02:52,738
that quickly builds that divide in the team.

74
00:02:52,738 --> 00:02:54,720
This is my job over here, that's yours over there,

75
00:02:54,720 --> 00:02:56,101
you stay over there, I got this.

76
00:02:56,101 --> 00:02:58,562
I've even interviewed a designer once

77
00:02:58,562 --> 00:02:59,803
who used this as their reasoning

78
00:02:59,803 --> 00:03:01,144
for wanting to leave their current position

79
00:03:01,144 --> 00:03:02,165
at their current studio.

80
00:03:02,165 --> 00:03:04,286
They felt that every time they pitched a design,

81
00:03:04,286 --> 00:03:06,127
other people on the team would give feedback

82
00:03:06,127 --> 00:03:08,169
and say certain things and pitch other designs.

83
00:03:08,169 --> 00:03:10,130
And I'm thinking, yeah, the nerve of those people,

84
00:03:10,130 --> 00:03:12,111
you know, wanting to have an input on their project.

85
00:03:13,551 --> 00:03:15,472
So when you have this mindset,

86
00:03:15,472 --> 00:03:17,813
what you're really telling the person is,

87
00:03:17,813 --> 00:03:19,174
what you're saying doesn't matter.

88
00:03:19,174 --> 00:03:20,935
Only what I say matters, I'm the designer.

89
00:03:20,935 --> 00:03:23,977
And it coincides nicely with our second one, I know best.

90
00:03:23,977 --> 00:03:26,439
Now this one's usually thrown around

91
00:03:26,439 --> 00:03:28,980
when the designer can't convince the other person

92
00:03:28,980 --> 00:03:29,541
of their point.

93
00:03:29,541 --> 00:03:31,842
But this is also something a parent says to their child.

94
00:03:31,842 --> 00:03:34,324
And just when the child grows up,

95
00:03:34,324 --> 00:03:35,345
they realize the parent's just been

96
00:03:35,345 --> 00:03:36,805
winging it the entire time.

97
00:03:36,805 --> 00:03:38,386
So just like with a parent, when you say this,

98
00:03:38,386 --> 00:03:41,028
what you're really saying is, I know best, you know nothing.

99
00:03:42,070 --> 00:03:45,762
You haven't really seen fireworks until you witness a junior designer say this to a 20-year

100
00:03:45,762 --> 00:03:47,669
vet engineer.

101
00:03:47,669 --> 00:03:48,692
That's an exciting time.

102
00:03:51,280 --> 00:03:53,641
Give me feedback, not designs or solutions.

103
00:03:53,641 --> 00:03:56,001
I've seen this one posted on social media

104
00:03:56,001 --> 00:03:58,902
as this positive message, and to me it made me cringe a bit.

105
00:03:58,902 --> 00:04:00,442
The issue here is more subtle.

106
00:04:00,442 --> 00:04:03,223
The designer doesn't want the person to add to the design.

107
00:04:03,223 --> 00:04:04,903
They want feedback on the experience they just played.

108
00:04:04,903 --> 00:04:06,604
They wanna know how it felt for them.

109
00:04:06,604 --> 00:04:09,244
But in reality, everything that person is saying is feedback.

110
00:04:09,244 --> 00:04:11,885
It's just not easy for people to really find the problem

111
00:04:11,885 --> 00:04:13,225
and tell you about it, so sometimes

112
00:04:13,225 --> 00:04:15,406
they jump straight to solutions.

113
00:04:15,406 --> 00:04:17,706
So what the designer is telling them is,

114
00:04:17,706 --> 00:04:19,506
tell me what I wanna hear the way I wanna hear it.

115
00:04:20,315 --> 00:04:22,056
and they're not really trained sometimes

116
00:04:22,056 --> 00:04:22,956
to talk in our language,

117
00:04:22,956 --> 00:04:24,317
and this statement may push them away

118
00:04:24,317 --> 00:04:25,498
to not give feedback in the future.

119
00:04:25,498 --> 00:04:29,880
This is the design we approved.

120
00:04:29,880 --> 00:04:31,721
So this one's usually said when someone gives feedback

121
00:04:31,721 --> 00:04:32,982
to an already approved design,

122
00:04:32,982 --> 00:04:35,683
and we as designers just don't wanna open that can of worms,

123
00:04:35,683 --> 00:04:38,285
we just got that design finalized maybe months ago,

124
00:04:38,285 --> 00:04:40,286
or we just want production to keep moving forward.

125
00:04:40,286 --> 00:04:42,447
But what it's really saying is,

126
00:04:42,447 --> 00:04:44,929
I don't wanna listen to you or reflect on feedback.

127
00:04:45,819 --> 00:04:48,782
It's saying that nothing has changed, that we as a team have learned nothing since the

128
00:04:48,782 --> 00:04:51,744
design was first written, we haven't seen the game progress, we don't have a deeper

129
00:04:51,744 --> 00:04:55,127
understanding of what the game is, that we can't look at an approved design and question

130
00:04:55,127 --> 00:04:56,748
its purpose in the grand scheme.

131
00:04:56,748 --> 00:04:57,729
And we all know that's never true.

132
00:04:59,957 --> 00:05:02,859
And finally, an old favorite, trust me.

133
00:05:02,859 --> 00:05:03,359
Just trust me.

134
00:05:03,359 --> 00:05:05,581
And the developer's of course thinking, trust you.

135
00:05:05,581 --> 00:05:07,422
Like seriously, why don't you trust me?

136
00:05:07,422 --> 00:05:09,824
Because you're the designer, you know best.

137
00:05:09,824 --> 00:05:10,884
My feedback doesn't matter

138
00:05:10,884 --> 00:05:14,126
because we already approved this design a while ago.

139
00:05:14,126 --> 00:05:16,308
I'm not gonna stay late when this all blows up.

140
00:05:16,308 --> 00:05:18,569
And there it is, that divide you kinda see

141
00:05:18,569 --> 00:05:19,850
in your day-to-day throughout the team.

142
00:05:19,850 --> 00:05:21,251
And I've seen this happen a lot.

143
00:05:22,220 --> 00:05:23,961
I've even seen developers storm out of the building

144
00:05:23,961 --> 00:05:25,543
because they're not being listened to,

145
00:05:25,543 --> 00:05:27,044
shouting matches on the floor,

146
00:05:27,044 --> 00:05:28,466
and worst of all, I've seen what can happen

147
00:05:28,466 --> 00:05:30,087
to an entire team that no longer believes

148
00:05:30,087 --> 00:05:31,508
in the game they're building.

149
00:05:31,508 --> 00:05:33,971
These mindsets lead to a destructive,

150
00:05:33,971 --> 00:05:35,652
I'm the designer, do what I say, culture.

151
00:05:35,652 --> 00:05:38,335
And as I went through these examples,

152
00:05:38,335 --> 00:05:39,736
I know some of you were thinking,

153
00:05:39,736 --> 00:05:40,757
crap, I said that last week.

154
00:05:40,757 --> 00:05:42,939
We've all been guilty of these,

155
00:05:42,939 --> 00:05:45,842
and honestly, I believe it stems from our biggest insecurity.

156
00:05:45,842 --> 00:05:47,003
Stop trying to do my job.

157
00:05:48,402 --> 00:05:50,043
As designers, we have chosen a profession

158
00:05:50,043 --> 00:05:51,263
that everyone wants to be a part of.

159
00:05:51,263 --> 00:05:52,984
And after all, everyone has ideas.

160
00:05:52,984 --> 00:05:55,365
But we also have this fear that if we don't have control

161
00:05:55,365 --> 00:05:57,386
and maintain control, that people on the team

162
00:05:57,386 --> 00:05:59,347
are just gonna be pitching ideas that don't work,

163
00:05:59,347 --> 00:06:01,447
don't fit our systems, they aren't what we're looking for,

164
00:06:01,447 --> 00:06:02,928
they're not coming together, they don't make sense,

165
00:06:02,928 --> 00:06:05,409
just give me some time, just let me design this,

166
00:06:05,409 --> 00:06:06,309
stop trying to do my job.

167
00:06:06,309 --> 00:06:08,590
Maybe that sounds familiar to some of you.

168
00:06:08,590 --> 00:06:10,571
But what is our job?

169
00:06:12,689 --> 00:06:14,690
Our job is to design perfect game loops, mechanics,

170
00:06:14,690 --> 00:06:16,792
and systems that engage our players and keep them hooked.

171
00:06:16,792 --> 00:06:18,494
And we do that, and they look great.

172
00:06:18,494 --> 00:06:20,555
Now, I know some of you are looking at this like,

173
00:06:20,555 --> 00:06:21,156
what game is that from?

174
00:06:21,156 --> 00:06:24,259
This is a filtration system to a swimming pool.

175
00:06:24,259 --> 00:06:26,901
Sort of just a metaphor.

176
00:06:26,901 --> 00:06:28,202
So we put this system into the game,

177
00:06:28,202 --> 00:06:29,684
and we connect it to all the other systems.

178
00:06:29,684 --> 00:06:33,087
But we can't do this section because the technical hurdle

179
00:06:33,087 --> 00:06:35,028
is too high, and the directors changed their mind

180
00:06:35,028 --> 00:06:37,751
on this piece, and we have some messaging issues here,

181
00:06:37,751 --> 00:06:39,632
and playtests came back with some frustrations here.

182
00:06:40,809 --> 00:06:42,349
and afterwards your perfect system

183
00:06:42,349 --> 00:06:43,450
sort of looks like a chewed up dog toy.

184
00:06:43,450 --> 00:06:47,152
But it's honestly the team that comes to the rescue.

185
00:06:47,152 --> 00:06:49,313
This idea of stop trying to do my job

186
00:06:49,313 --> 00:06:52,555
quickly becomes hey guys, can you help me fix this?

187
00:06:52,555 --> 00:06:54,516
The UI team finds a solution for this piece,

188
00:06:54,516 --> 00:06:56,217
the gameplay team reroutes this section,

189
00:06:56,217 --> 00:06:58,758
and the art team pitches a cheaper solution to this.

190
00:07:00,293 --> 00:07:02,814
In the end, game design always becomes a team effort.

191
00:07:02,814 --> 00:07:04,574
Designers, we need to ditch that insecurity,

192
00:07:04,574 --> 00:07:06,195
we need to let the rest of the team in,

193
00:07:06,195 --> 00:07:07,235
and we need to learn to lead.

194
00:07:07,235 --> 00:07:09,356
Because the best teams I've worked with

195
00:07:09,356 --> 00:07:11,177
are ones where everyone feels engaged

196
00:07:11,177 --> 00:07:13,017
and invested in the experience they're making.

197
00:07:13,017 --> 00:07:14,358
Now of course, I'm not saying everyone

198
00:07:14,358 --> 00:07:15,298
should design their own sections.

199
00:07:15,298 --> 00:07:17,439
Everything still needs to come together

200
00:07:17,439 --> 00:07:19,339
in a cohesive vision.

201
00:07:19,339 --> 00:07:21,500
And for designers, sharing that vision

202
00:07:21,500 --> 00:07:22,561
leads us to our first soft skill

203
00:07:22,561 --> 00:07:24,921
for building a positive design culture.

204
00:07:24,921 --> 00:07:26,602
The ability to inspire.

205
00:07:27,667 --> 00:07:29,489
Now most designers know how to communicate their vision,

206
00:07:29,489 --> 00:07:30,991
but few know how to inspire with it.

207
00:07:30,991 --> 00:07:34,094
Communication ends with people understanding design,

208
00:07:34,094 --> 00:07:35,655
inspiration ends with them believing in it.

209
00:07:35,655 --> 00:07:37,757
The time of I'm the designer, do what I say,

210
00:07:37,757 --> 00:07:38,478
that's long gone.

211
00:07:38,478 --> 00:07:41,301
Developers are gonna devote the next three to five years

212
00:07:41,301 --> 00:07:43,062
of their career on your designs,

213
00:07:43,062 --> 00:07:43,983
they need to believe in them.

214
00:07:43,983 --> 00:07:45,525
And if they don't believe,

215
00:07:45,525 --> 00:07:47,186
honestly they'll never stop questioning.

216
00:07:47,186 --> 00:07:50,330
But getting them to believe isn't as hard as you think.

217
00:07:51,634 --> 00:07:54,236
It all starts with the design goals of the feature,

218
00:07:54,236 --> 00:07:57,299
the problems you're trying to solve with the design itself.

219
00:07:57,299 --> 00:07:59,141
And for a quick example, I'm gonna turn to the war meter

220
00:07:59,141 --> 00:08:00,262
for Starlink Battle for Atlas.

221
00:08:03,146 --> 00:08:06,848
This vertical meter on the right displays the current state of the conflict on the planet.

222
00:08:06,848 --> 00:08:10,069
It shows who owns more ground, your alliance or the legion enemy.

223
00:08:10,069 --> 00:08:12,530
The goals of this feature are listed in priority order.

224
00:08:12,530 --> 00:08:17,012
To display the status of the planetary conflict, to give more meaning to the player's action

225
00:08:17,012 --> 00:08:20,934
by showing the impact they're having on the world, and to push that feeling of the enemy

226
00:08:20,934 --> 00:08:23,255
as an oppressive and dominating force.

227
00:08:23,255 --> 00:08:26,936
The perfect goals are things everybody wants and nobody could say no to.

228
00:08:27,577 --> 00:08:29,437
These goals should drive everything,

229
00:08:29,437 --> 00:08:31,638
all discussion, all design, all brainstorms,

230
00:08:31,638 --> 00:08:33,718
and later on I'll show you how they end up

231
00:08:33,718 --> 00:08:36,919
resolving most disagreements.

232
00:08:36,919 --> 00:08:38,719
So before you even start designing,

233
00:08:38,719 --> 00:08:40,100
create a set of two to three goals

234
00:08:40,100 --> 00:08:41,560
and pitch a few of them to your peers.

235
00:08:41,560 --> 00:08:43,560
Use their help to strengthen these goals.

236
00:08:43,560 --> 00:08:44,881
Get them excited about these goals.

237
00:08:44,881 --> 00:08:46,261
If people don't believe in your goals,

238
00:08:46,261 --> 00:08:47,962
they're honestly not gonna believe in your design.

239
00:08:47,962 --> 00:08:50,382
With this process, you're not only gaining believers,

240
00:08:50,382 --> 00:08:51,742
you're actually gaining advocates.

241
00:08:51,742 --> 00:08:53,203
These advocates will resolve smaller issues

242
00:08:53,203 --> 00:08:55,723
across the team that you don't even realize are there.

243
00:08:58,114 --> 00:08:59,735
And step two to inspiring the team,

244
00:08:59,735 --> 00:09:01,175
sell the goals then to the people

245
00:09:01,175 --> 00:09:02,936
that will implement the feature.

246
00:09:02,936 --> 00:09:05,557
And with their input, build design that achieves those goals.

247
00:09:05,557 --> 00:09:08,199
The design isn't finished until they fully believe in it.

248
00:09:08,199 --> 00:09:09,399
Now I know some of you are worried

249
00:09:09,399 --> 00:09:11,220
that this process feels a bit time intensive,

250
00:09:11,220 --> 00:09:14,561
but honestly the time spent building a design with the devs

251
00:09:14,561 --> 00:09:16,142
will save you in the long run at the end

252
00:09:16,142 --> 00:09:17,743
when you're trying to clean up that mess of pipes

253
00:09:17,743 --> 00:09:18,223
I showed you earlier.

254
00:09:18,223 --> 00:09:19,163
And step three, pitch all of it to the team.

255
00:09:24,511 --> 00:09:26,712
As always, you're going to start with the goals,

256
00:09:26,712 --> 00:09:28,554
because the team believes in the goals,

257
00:09:28,554 --> 00:09:30,355
