00:18:47,965 --> 00:18:49,545
because they're not seeing the whole picture.

517
00:18:49,545 --> 00:18:51,606
The UI team is just focused on the smaller portion.

518
00:18:51,606 --> 00:18:54,588
And a fair amount of the time that may be true

519
00:18:54,588 --> 00:18:56,528
because it's our job to hold the entire vision

520
00:18:56,528 --> 00:18:58,189
and how everything's gonna come together

521
00:18:58,189 --> 00:19:00,450
whereas other teams are focused on specific sections.

522
00:19:00,450 --> 00:19:03,812
But when do we stop trusting our vision

523
00:19:03,812 --> 00:19:05,052
and start trusting the skeptics?

524
00:19:07,552 --> 00:19:09,152
Let's take one last look at an example

525
00:19:09,152 --> 00:19:10,893
from the war meter in Starlink.

526
00:19:10,893 --> 00:19:13,194
The first feedback I received about this feature

527
00:19:13,194 --> 00:19:15,415
came from a tester who was just very confused

528
00:19:15,415 --> 00:19:16,816
as to how this was calculated.

529
00:19:16,816 --> 00:19:18,737
The bar shows, and so I explained,

530
00:19:18,737 --> 00:19:21,378
the bar shows who has control of the planet

531
00:19:21,378 --> 00:19:23,199
and it's determined by the number of bases

532
00:19:23,199 --> 00:19:24,820
you have versus the enemy.

533
00:19:24,820 --> 00:19:26,941
Except these dueling bases are not built

534
00:19:26,941 --> 00:19:28,401
on the same plots of land.

535
00:19:28,401 --> 00:19:30,703
This was to allow these bases to exist all at once

536
00:19:30,703 --> 00:19:32,443
so you get this epic war feeling on the planet.

537
00:19:35,115 --> 00:19:38,177
So as the player gains allies, by building bases,

538
00:19:38,177 --> 00:19:39,218
their meter's gonna fill up.

539
00:19:39,218 --> 00:19:41,359
On the other end, you have the enemy called the Legion.

540
00:19:41,359 --> 00:19:45,142
One of our goals, you might remember,

541
00:19:45,142 --> 00:19:46,363
was for them to feel oppressive

542
00:19:46,363 --> 00:19:48,324
and feel like this dominating force.

543
00:19:48,324 --> 00:19:50,606
Their bar doesn't stop growing when it meets yours.

544
00:19:50,606 --> 00:19:52,668
It engulfs it, just like they engulf the planet.

545
00:19:52,668 --> 00:19:55,530
This overlapping section is owned by the Legion.

546
00:19:57,451 --> 00:19:59,412
At this point, the only way to push your alliance higher

547
00:19:59,412 --> 00:20:00,232
is to destroy their bases.

548
00:20:00,232 --> 00:20:03,513
This gives you the room you need to expand your alliance.

549
00:20:03,513 --> 00:20:04,934
After I explained this to the tester,

550
00:20:04,934 --> 00:20:07,375
he understood, went on his way, everything seemed fine.

551
00:20:07,375 --> 00:20:11,176
But then the second red flag came from an engineer

552
00:20:11,176 --> 00:20:13,257
who repeated that concern, that confusion

553
00:20:13,257 --> 00:20:14,677
about how the bar was calculated.

554
00:20:14,677 --> 00:20:17,218
Again, I explained the goals, he understood,

555
00:20:17,218 --> 00:20:19,799
and then the third strike came from a level designer.

556
00:20:19,799 --> 00:20:22,000
At this point, I stopped selling the goals.

557
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:22,560
Something was wrong.

558
00:20:24,307 --> 00:20:27,469
The overlap owned by the Legion was causing confusion and frustration.

559
00:20:27,469 --> 00:20:30,671
There were a few solutions to this problem, but honestly the easiest one was to pull back

560
00:20:30,671 --> 00:20:34,914
on my goal of the Legion feeling like an oppressive force and adjust how we calculate this meter.

561
00:20:34,914 --> 00:20:39,778
We ended up making the meter average out between both factions, so there was a constant tug

562
00:20:39,778 --> 00:20:40,158
of war.

563
00:20:40,158 --> 00:20:44,741
Now the shipping product had a less dominating Legion, one that just engulfs you easily,

564
00:20:44,741 --> 00:20:47,383
and in hindsight though, this was always the better option.

565
00:20:48,515 --> 00:20:52,238
I use this as an example of how designers can get too entrenched in a goal or an idea.

566
00:20:52,238 --> 00:20:56,561
We must have a process that forces us to stop and think differently.

567
00:20:56,561 --> 00:20:58,202
And this one's mine.

568
00:20:58,202 --> 00:21:00,584
Step one, defend the vision.

569
00:21:00,584 --> 00:21:03,386
Every decision you've made up to this point has had a team behind it.

570
00:21:03,386 --> 00:21:06,488
We've built great goals the team believes in.

571
00:21:06,488 --> 00:21:10,532
We follow that up with the design we've built with the devs that achieves those goals.

572
00:21:12,655 --> 00:21:14,938
Step two, listen to feedback with patience and understanding.

573
00:21:14,938 --> 00:21:17,019
Get to the bottom of everything they're saying

574
00:21:17,019 --> 00:21:17,880
and discuss solutions.

575
00:21:17,880 --> 00:21:20,823
But the last issue arises when the solution

576
00:21:20,823 --> 00:21:23,045
goes against your goals and you still strongly believe

577
00:21:23,045 --> 00:21:24,847
in those goals, just in my previous war effort example.

578
00:21:24,847 --> 00:21:30,172
And when three people on the team of different backgrounds

579
00:21:30,172 --> 00:21:32,394
say the same thing, it's time to stop and reflect.

580
00:21:32,394 --> 00:21:35,777
The exact number of strikes is gonna change for each team

581
00:21:35,777 --> 00:21:37,999
and now that I've publicly announced mine is three,

582
00:21:37,999 --> 00:21:38,940
I probably need to increase it.

583
00:21:40,082 --> 00:21:43,463
But the point here is to have a limit when you stop defending your goals and start changing

584
00:21:43,463 --> 00:21:44,223
your perspective.

585
00:21:44,223 --> 00:21:47,264
And just let everyone know the reason it's not one is because you can't spend your entire

586
00:21:47,264 --> 00:21:53,925
career rethinking everything every time someone brings something up.

587
00:21:53,925 --> 00:21:57,446
So to recap, trust me becomes I trust you.

588
00:21:58,520 --> 00:22:01,142
The purpose of building trust isn't so everyone leaves us alone.

589
00:22:01,142 --> 00:22:03,964
The purpose is to build an environment where all team members can be heard,

590
00:22:03,964 --> 00:22:06,266
because we trust each other to want what's best for the game.

591
00:22:06,266 --> 00:22:09,668
And of course, when we falter, the others are going to be there

592
00:22:09,668 --> 00:22:11,049
to get things, pick us back up.

593
00:22:11,049 --> 00:22:12,951
Yes, more Saturday morning cartoon stuff.

594
00:22:12,951 --> 00:22:15,112
And there you have it.

595
00:22:15,112 --> 00:22:18,375
These are the soft skills I believe every designer needs

596
00:22:18,375 --> 00:22:20,576
to create a positive design culture at a studio.

597
00:22:20,576 --> 00:22:22,958
A culture where everyone feels invested in the game's success.

598
00:22:22,958 --> 00:22:25,220
And these, of course, spark the soft skills.

599
00:22:26,025 --> 00:22:28,866
of the designer mindsets that will dismantle all walls

600
00:22:28,866 --> 00:22:31,667
between design and the rest of the team.

601
00:22:31,667 --> 00:22:33,828
Our job is to ensure that every developer on a team

602
00:22:33,828 --> 00:22:35,969
believes in each and every one of their tasks,

603
00:22:35,969 --> 00:22:38,090
because they understand and believe in the goals

604
00:22:38,090 --> 00:22:39,390
that that task will achieve.

605
00:22:39,390 --> 00:22:41,451
They believe in the game that we're trying to make.

606
00:22:41,451 --> 00:22:44,172
The best culture is one with team ownership,

607
00:22:44,172 --> 00:22:45,753
a team-driven approval process,

608
00:22:45,753 --> 00:22:47,013
and full team collaboration,

609
00:22:47,013 --> 00:22:49,054
because the game doesn't belong to designers,

610
00:22:49,054 --> 00:22:49,895
it belongs to the team.

611
00:22:51,702 --> 00:22:53,486
So this is a design culture I promote on my teams,

612
00:22:53,486 --> 00:22:56,212
and I strongly believe it can help resolve conflicts

613
00:22:56,212 --> 00:22:57,795
and promote teamwork across the industry.

